  <body style="background-color: #ffcc66;">
    <h1 style="background-color: #ffcc66; text-align: center;">ICS 6N - Winter
      2018<br>
      Lab 3: Matrix Algebra</h1>
    <hr>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="center"><font
        face="Times New Roman"
        size="4">3.1
        Introduction</font></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      The purpose of this lab is to make you feel comfortable using MATLAB to
      perform various operations with matrices.&nbsp; In some sense, matrices
      are a bit like real numbers: they can be added, subtracted, and multiplied
      (provided they have appropriate dimensions).&nbsp; Certain square matrices
      can also be inverted.&nbsp; However, with these similarities also come
      some striking differences.&nbsp; For example, when multiplying matrices,
      it is not true in general that<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>AB</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>BA</b>,
      and<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sup>2</sup><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>may
      equal<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>0</b><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>even
      for nonzero<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b>.&nbsp;
      Keep these things in mind as you are working through this lab; it will
      help build up your intuition about matrices.</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      Matrix algebra is not just some crazy theoretical nonsense that people
      made up when they got bored with real numbers.&nbsp; You will see how we
      can apply these ideas to a concrete real world problem.&nbsp; Hopefully,
      you will enjoy seeing matrices being applied to everyday life.</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="center"><font
        size="4">3.2
        Addition and Multiplication</font></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      You have already seen that we can add two matrices of the same dimensions
      by adding their corresponding entries.&nbsp; The operator MATLAB uses to
      add matrices is simply '+', as the next example shows:</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><font
        color="#6600cc"><b>Example
          3.1<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></b></font>&nbsp;</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      Let us first enter some matrices into MATLAB:</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
          color="#990000">A
          = [1, 2, 3, 4; 5, 6, 7, 8]</font></tt><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><br>
      <tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font color="#990000">B
          = [8, 7, 6, 5; 4, 3, 2, 1]</font></tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">We
      can add them by typing</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
          color="#990000">A+B</font></tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><tt>ans
        =<br>
        <br>
        9&nbsp;&nbsp; 9&nbsp;&nbsp; 9&nbsp;&nbsp; 9<br>
        9&nbsp;&nbsp; 9&nbsp;&nbsp; 9&nbsp;&nbsp; 9</tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      As you know, matrix addition is defined componentwise, but matrix
      multiplication is defined in a way that may seem strange at first
      glance.&nbsp; However, this way of defining matrix multiplication turns
      out to work to our advantage in the future.&nbsp; You may have seen some
      of the motivation for this definition in lecture.&nbsp; To recap, recall
      that if we have a matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>of
      dimension<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>k x l</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>and
      a matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>B</b><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>of
      dimension<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>l x m</i>, we
      can multiply them to obtain a<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>k
        x m</i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>AB</b>.&nbsp;
      Note that in order to be able to multiply two matrices, the number of
      columns of the first one must be the same as the number of rows of the
      second one.&nbsp; For your convenience here is the definition:</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="center"><font
        size="4">(<b>AB</b>)<i><sub>ij</sub></i></font><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
        face="Times New Roman"
        size="5">âˆ‘</font><font
        face="Times New Roman"><i><span
            class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i><font
          size="4"><b>A</b><i><sub>in</sub></i><b>B</b></font><i><sub><font
              size="4">nj</font></sub></i></font></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">Here
      (<b>AB</b>)<i><sub>ij</sub></i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>represents
      the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>ij</i><sup>th</sup><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>entry
      of the matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>AB</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>and<font
        face="Times New Roman"><span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>n</i><span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>runs
        from 1 to<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>l</i><span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>in
        the summation.</font></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left"><b><font
          color="#6600cc">Example
          3.2</font></b></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left"><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></b>Enter
      the following matrices into MATLAB:</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
          color="#990000">A
          = [1, 1; 1, 0]</font></tt><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><br>
      <tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font color="#990000">B
          = [0, 1; 1, 1]</font></tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">Now
      multiply them, simply by typing</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
          color="#990000">A*B</font></tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left"><tt>ans
        =<br>
        <br>
        1&nbsp;&nbsp; 2<br>
        0&nbsp;&nbsp; 1</tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">What
      happens if we multiply<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>B</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>by<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b>?</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
          color="#990000">B*A</font></tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left"><tt>ans
        =<br>
        <br>
        1&nbsp;&nbsp; 0<br>
        2&nbsp;&nbsp; 1</tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">When
      you multiply two matrices<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>and<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>B</b>,
      it is often not true that<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>AB</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>BA</b>!</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">&nbsp;</p>
    <table border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2" width="100%">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td valign="top" width="1092"><b><font color="#009900" size="-0">Exercise
                3.1&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></font></b>Can
            you think of any 2x2 matrices<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>D</b><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>for
            which<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>CD</b><i><span
                class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
                class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i><b>DC</b><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>for
            all 2x2 matrices<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>C</b>?&nbsp;
            Give 2 different examples of such matrices<b>D</b>.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      We can do other things with matrices as well. Among things to try are:<br>
    </p>
    <table id="AutoNumber9" style="border-collapse: collapse;" border="0" bordercolor="#111111"
      cellpadding="0"
      cellspacing="0"
      width="900">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td width="89"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                color="#990000">A-B</font></tt></td>
          <td width="808">
            <p align="left">(Subtracts two matrices.)</p>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="89"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                color="#990000">2*A</font></tt></td>
          <td width="808">(Multiplies matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>by
            a scalar<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>2</i>.)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="89"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                color="#990000">A^3</font></tt></td>
          <td width="808">(Raises the matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>to
            the third power, i.e., multiplies<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>by
            itself three times.)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="89"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                color="#990000">A.*B</font></tt></td>
          <td width="808">(Multiplies the corresponding entries of the matrices
            together. We will not be using this command, but it is nice to
            know.)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="89"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                color="#990000">rref(A)</font></tt></td>
          <td width="808">(Gives the reduced row echelon form of<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b>.)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="89"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                color="#990000">A'</font></tt></td>
          <td width="808">(Gives the transpose of<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b>,
            sometimes written as<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sup>T</sup>)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="left">where<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>A</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>and<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>B</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>are
      the same matrices defined in the above example.</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
