    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="center"><font
        size="4">3.3
        Application: Incidence Matrices</font></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      Consider the following problem: suppose we have six cities with airports,
      say San Diego, San Francisco, Chicago, New York, Moscow, and Tokyo.&nbsp;
      We are interested in counting the number of ways we can travel from one
      city to another with at most<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>n</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>stopovers.&nbsp;
      Suppose for example that there are direct flights from</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">San
      Diego to San Francisco<br>
      San Francisco to any of the remaining five cities<br>
      Chicago to San Francisco, New York, and Moscow<br>
      New York to San Diego, San Francisco, Chicago, and Moscow<br>
      Moscow to Chicago, New York, and Tokyo<br>
      Tokyo to San Francisco, New York, and Moscow</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">and
      we want to count the number of ways we can get from San Diego to Moscow
      with at most 3 stopovers.&nbsp; For example, the trip San Diego - San
      Francisco - Tokyo - New York - Moscow is a trip with 3 stopovers.&nbsp;
      (We are stopping over in San Francisco, Tokyo, and New York).&nbsp; Let us
      get a taste for this problem in the next exercise.</p>
    <table id="AutoNumber2" style="font-family: Times; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      border="2"
      cellpadding="2"
      width="100%">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td width="95%"><font color="#009900"><b>Exercise 3.3</b>&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></font>List
            all possible ways to get from San Diego to Moscow with exactly 3
            stopovers.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      At first glance this problem has little to do with matrices and linear
      algebra, but it turns out that there is a very easy and elegant way of
      solving problems of this type using something called<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>incidence
        matrices</i>.</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      The first step is to number our cities in the order they are listed: San
      Diego will be 1, San Francisco 2, and so on.&nbsp; Then, let us set up our
      incidence matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><i><span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i>by
      the following rule: if we can get from the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>i</i><sup>th</sup><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>city
      to the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>j</i><sup>th</sup><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>city,
      then the entry<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><i><sub>ij</sub></i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>of
      the matrix will be set to 1.&nbsp; Otherwise we set that entry to 0.&nbsp;
      By convention we will set all of the diagonal entries,<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><i><sub>i</sub></i><sub><i>i</i></sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>to
      0, because you cannot take a flight from a city to itself.&nbsp; Thus we
      obtain the following matrix<i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i><b>A</b><i><span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i>for
      our situation:</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="center"><img
        alt=""
        src="http://www.ics.uci.edu/%7Eirani/f13-6N/Labs/Lab3_Files/incdnce.gif"
        style="border: 0px solid; width: 137px; height: 135px;"></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">We
      can now find a useful interpretation for the entries of the matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sup>2</sup>.
      Take, for example:</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">(<b>A</b><sup>2</sup>)<sub>36</sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>31</sub><b>A</b><sub>16</sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>+<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>32</sub><b>A</b><sub>26</sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>+<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>33</sub><b>A</b><sub>36</sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>+<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>34</sub><b>A</b><sub>46</sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>+<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>35</sub><b>A</b><sub>56</sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>+<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>36</sub><b>A</b><sub>66</sub></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">Note
      that any of the terms<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>3<i>k</i></sub><b>A</b><sub><i>k</i>6</sub><i><span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i>1
      if and only if both<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub>3<i>k</i></sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>and<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sub><i>k</i>6</sub><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>equal
      1; that is, if and only if we can fly from Chicago to the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>k</i><sup>th</sup><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>city
      and from the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>k</i><sup>th</sup><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>city
      to Tokyo.&nbsp; Thus (<b>A</b><sup>2</sup>)<sub>36<i>&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i></sub>gives
      us the number of ways of flying from Chicago to Tokyo with exactly one
      stopover.&nbsp; Similarly one can show that the number of ways of flying
      from city<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>i</i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>to
      city<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>j</i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>with<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>exactly</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>n</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>stopovers
      is just (<b>A</b><i><sup>n+1</sup></i>)<i><sub>ij</sub></i>.</p>
    <table id="AutoNumber2" style="font-family: Times; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      border="2"
      cellpadding="2"
      width="100%">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td colspan="2" width="100%"><font color="#009900"><b>Exercise 3.4</b></font></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="95%"><b><font color="#009900">(a)</font>&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></b>Go
            ahead and enter the above incidence matrix into MATLAB by typing in
            the following command:<br>
            <p><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                  color="#990000">A
                  = [0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0;</font></tt><br>
              <tt><font color="#990000">1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1;<br>
                  0, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0;<br>
                  1, 1, 1, 0, 1, 0;<br>
                  0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1;<br>
                  0, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0]</font></tt></p>
            <p>Now state the number of ways to get from San Diego to Moscow with
              exactly 3 stopovers.&nbsp; Simply type in:</p>
            <p><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                  color="#990000">A^4</font></tt></p>
            <p>and read off the entry in the first row and fifth column.&nbsp;
              Does your answer agree with your explicit count in exercise
              3.3?&nbsp; If not, find the missing trips.&nbsp; Include your
              input and output in the final Word document.</p>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="95%"><b><font color="#009900">(b)</font>&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></b>Find
            the number of ways to get from San Francisco to Chicago with<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>at
              most</i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>4
            stopovers.&nbsp; (Note, this is<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>not<span
                class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i>the
            same as finding the number of ways with<i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>exactly</i><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>4
            stopovers!)<i>&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i>Include
            all of your commands and output in your final write up.</td>
