      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><b><font
          color="#ff6600">Remark
          3.1</font></b>&nbsp; As you have probably realized, the method
      discussed above counts silly trips such as San Francisco<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
        face="Times New Roman">â†’</font><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>New
      York<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font face="Times New Roman">â†’</font><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>San
      Francisco<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font face="Times New Roman">â†’</font><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>New
      York as a trip with 2 stopovers, so, user beware!</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      align="center"><font
        size="4">3.4
        Matrix Inversion</font></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      A concept of fundamental importance is that of the inverse of a
      matrix.&nbsp; Recall that we define the inverse of an<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>n
        x n<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></i>matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>to
      be a matrix<b>B</b><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>such
      that<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>AB</b><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>BA</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=<span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>I</b>,
      where<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>I</b><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>is
      the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>n x n</i><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>identity
      matrix.&nbsp; Such a matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>B</b><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>is
      denoted by<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><sup>-1</sup>.&nbsp;
      Note that it follows from the definition that<b>B</b><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>is
      also an&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>n x n</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>matrix.&nbsp;</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">As
      we know, every nonzero real number<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>x</i><span
        class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>has
      an inverse, namely<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>1/x</i>.&nbsp;
      However, this need not be the case with non-zero matrices, which may be
      invertible (sometimes called<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><i>non-singular</i>)
      or non-invertible (<i>singular</i>). MATLAB has a special command,<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><tt><font
          color="#990000">inv</font></tt>,
      that finds the inverse of a matrix, if one exists.</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      If you want to find an inverse of a square matrix M, simply type</p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><tt>&gt;&gt;<span
          class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
          color="#990000">inv(M)</font></tt></p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      (Of course, if you enter this right now you'll probably get an error. We
      haven't defined a matrix M.)</p>
    <table id="AutoNumber4" style="font-family: Times; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"
      border="2"
      cellpadding="2"
      width="100%">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td colspan="2" width="100%"><font color="#009900"><b>Exercise 3.5</b></font></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="100%"><b><font color="#009900">(a)&nbsp;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></font></b>Try
            using the<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><tt><font
                color="#990000">inv</font></tt><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>command
            to find the inverse of the matrix&nbsp;
            <p><img alt="" src="http://www.ics.uci.edu/%7Eirani/f13-6N/Labs/Lab3_Files/ex3img1.gif"
                style="border: 0px solid; width: 85px; height: 46px;"><span
                class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>Notice the strange output.&nbsp; Include your command and the
              output in the final write up.</p>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td width="95%"><font color="#009900"><b>(b)</b></font>&nbsp; Now
            enter the following matrix<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><b>A</b><span
              class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>into
            MATLAB.
            <p><tt>&gt;&gt;<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><font
                  color="#990000">A
